WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.640
I am going to start off this presentation with every software engineer's favorite thing

00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:16.480
to see, which is an open GitHub issue.

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:21.600
So the issue that is on the screen right now is from the Flex Dashboard GitHub page, and

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:26.959
Flex Dashboard is widely regarded as one of the easiest ways to get a Shiny app dashboard

00:00:26.959 --> 00:00:29.040
up and running.

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:34.080
Here the GitHub user is asking how to make a pretty straightforward app with a dashboard

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:39.639
layout that appears to be tackling the seriously troubling issue of cookie theft.

00:00:39.639 --> 00:00:40.639
The layout is simple.

00:00:40.639 --> 00:00:46.480
There are two rows, with the top row having a tab set on the left, and a terribly troubling

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:49.360
plot with an upward trajectory on the right.

00:00:49.360 --> 00:00:54.880
The bottom is a large panel that spans the entire width, and it's surely going to be

00:00:54.880 --> 00:00:57.759
filled with some very depressing data.

00:00:57.759 --> 00:01:01.639
But there are a few interesting things about this screenshot that I want to draw your attention

00:01:01.639 --> 00:01:02.639
to.

00:01:02.639 --> 00:01:03.639
Yeah.

00:01:03.639 --> 00:01:04.639
Okay.

00:01:04.639 --> 00:01:06.639
Is this better?

00:01:06.639 --> 00:01:07.639
Okay.

00:01:07.639 --> 00:01:12.099
So one of the first things I want to draw your attention to is that this issue was opened

00:01:12.099 --> 00:01:17.419
in May of 2016, also known as the before times.

00:01:17.419 --> 00:01:22.400
So imagine the devastation on cookie supplies that have been wrought in the six years that

00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:26.519
this GitHub user has been waiting to build this dashboard.

00:01:26.519 --> 00:01:32.720
So next is below, which is the thumbs up emoji responses, and there are 18 of them,

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:36.720
which is by far the most up-thumbed issue on this repo.

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:42.559
So clearly other users have been equally troubled by burglary of a confectionary nature.

00:01:42.559 --> 00:01:46.400
So why is this issue still open?

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:52.879
If we scroll down, you can actually see this is JJ's response, which is you can't actually

00:01:52.879 --> 00:01:55.639
create this right now.

00:01:55.639 --> 00:01:59.279
So at this point, you might be wondering why I would dedicate kind of the first section

00:01:59.279 --> 00:02:04.559
of my talk to pointing out the shortcomings of software written by the CEO of the company

00:02:04.559 --> 00:02:07.440
that I work for.

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:12.919
And really, I think it's worth it, because I think it perfectly encapsulates and motivates

00:02:12.919 --> 00:02:16.520
the work that I'm about to show.

00:02:16.520 --> 00:02:22.960
So if you went to Joe's keynote, he mentioned this in a similar way, but I really view Shiny's

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:28.839
superpower as being this force multiplier, as Joe puts it, for data scientists to share

00:02:28.839 --> 00:02:31.279
their work to a broader audience.

00:02:31.279 --> 00:02:35.880
But really, there's one kind of hiccup in that, one kind of hurdle that we've placed

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:39.839
in front of data scientists in using Shiny.

00:02:39.839 --> 00:02:43.520
And to understand what that is, I kind of want to start with a question, which is what

00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:46.960
is not crucial to doing great data science?

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:52.759
There's a lot of correct answers to this question, but the one I'm going for is understanding

00:02:52.759 --> 00:02:58.119
the tangled, terrible web of getting the browser to show what you want and where you

00:02:58.119 --> 00:02:59.119
want it.

00:02:59.119 --> 00:03:02.479
So Shiny does a pretty decent job of this already.

00:03:02.479 --> 00:03:05.960
We have helper functions, but it could be better.

00:03:05.960 --> 00:03:09.199
Like why did this GitHub issue have to be posted?

00:03:09.199 --> 00:03:14.960
Why did this user have trouble building an app that they could so clearly draw out?

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:19.139
Shouldn't that be enough to create your app?

00:03:19.139 --> 00:03:24.300
So more concretely, I want to ask the question of how can we make constructing the UI of

00:03:24.300 --> 00:03:29.059
your Shiny app take less time and just generally be more enjoyable?

00:03:29.059 --> 00:03:33.059
So we want you, the data scientists, to be freed up to do data science and not fiddle

00:03:33.059 --> 00:03:34.899
with your UI code.

00:03:34.899 --> 00:03:38.860
And this has really been a big focus of the Shiny team for a while now.

00:03:38.860 --> 00:03:43.059
And I've been personally working on it for more than a year and have come up with two

00:03:43.059 --> 00:03:47.339
fairly complementary paths to try to address this question.

00:03:47.339 --> 00:03:53.699
The first one is how do we make declaring your app layout more straightforward and intuitive?

00:03:53.699 --> 00:04:01.020
And the other one is how do we provide a new way of writing the UI code for your app?

00:04:01.020 --> 00:04:04.699
So I'm going to start with the first question, which is how do we make declaring the layout

00:04:04.699 --> 00:04:07.860
of your app a little bit more intuitive and straightforward?

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:13.139
The answer that we're proposing here is called grid layout.

00:04:13.139 --> 00:04:15.139
So what is grid layout?

00:04:15.139 --> 00:04:21.100
First and foremost, grid layout is an R packet, and it provides a simple interface for laying

00:04:21.100 --> 00:04:25.260
out complex data dashboards.

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:31.500
And also it's built on a thing called CSS grid, which is a spec, CSS built right into

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:32.500
your browser.

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:37.440
So there's no external libraries or JavaScript that needs to be run to work.

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:40.980
And also because it's built into your browser, it's not going to be abandoned.

00:04:40.980 --> 00:04:45.179
And the project isn't going to be left and not work late.

00:04:45.179 --> 00:04:48.140
So how do we actually go about using grid layout?

00:04:48.140 --> 00:04:51.739
I'm going to give you a quick example in code.

00:04:51.739 --> 00:04:55.619
And so we start by using a grid layout aware container.

00:04:55.619 --> 00:05:00.940
In this case, we're using grid page, we have other containers for doing like nesting grids,

00:05:00.940 --> 00:05:02.660
or putting them in more traditional apps.

00:05:02.660 --> 00:05:08.299
But here we're doing grid page, which lays out your entire app page with grid layout.

00:05:08.299 --> 00:05:10.339
So after that, we define the layout.

00:05:10.339 --> 00:05:13.540
And here, this is the layout defined, it's a table.

00:05:13.540 --> 00:05:17.660
But the table is represented as a character vector, where there's two elements, and each

00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:20.579
element represent the row of your layout.

00:05:20.579 --> 00:05:27.100
And then each column of your layout is represented as basically one or more spaces.

00:05:27.100 --> 00:05:30.619
And this one or more spaces rule allows you to line things up like you see here.

00:05:30.619 --> 00:05:36.420
So on the top, we have two columns that say tabs, next to that we have cookies, and then

00:05:36.420 --> 00:05:39.779
on the bottom, we just have bottom all the way across.

00:05:39.779 --> 00:05:47.339
So then to place items in this grid, you just use grid card, the familiar syntax, kind of

00:05:47.339 --> 00:05:48.500
like tab set panel.

00:05:48.500 --> 00:05:53.739
So here, like at the top, we use grid card, and we place it in the tabs area of the layout

00:05:53.739 --> 00:05:58.339
that we've just defined, using area equals tab, we just have to match each one of those

00:05:58.339 --> 00:06:03.739
areas to grid card or friends such as grid card plot.

00:06:03.739 --> 00:06:07.579
And this is the output of that exact code that you just saw.

00:06:07.579 --> 00:06:14.140
And it looks pretty similar to something we've already seen, which is the layout that the

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:18.260
Flex Dashboard GitHub issue is requesting.

00:06:18.260 --> 00:06:21.579
And so this kind of feels pretty simple.

00:06:21.579 --> 00:06:24.779
But really, it covers most of what grid layout does.

00:06:24.779 --> 00:06:29.299
And really, grid layout's whole goal is to be this very simple way, I can think of an

00:06:29.540 --> 00:06:33.940
I can draw it in a text table, I can make my

00:06:37.380 --> 00:06:40.260
Okay, so that's the first way that we've tackled this.

00:06:40.260 --> 00:06:44.299
How do we make constructing the UI Shiny app more enjoyable?

00:06:44.739 --> 00:06:45.940
So let's look at the next way.

00:06:45.940 --> 00:06:50.140
And the next way is how can we provide a new way of writing the UI code for your app?

00:06:51.619 --> 00:06:56.619
And the solution that we're proposing here is called Shiny UI Editor.

00:06:57.619 --> 00:07:02.619
So the name may give some of it away, and also Joe's keynote yesterday may have given

00:07:02.619 --> 00:07:03.619
some of it away.

00:07:03.619 --> 00:07:07.619
But let's quickly clarify what the Shiny UI Editor is.

00:07:07.619 --> 00:07:13.619
So the Shiny UI Editor is a drag and drop visual editor for your Shiny app UI.

00:07:13.619 --> 00:07:18.619
So this GIF that you're seeing kind of demonstrates that in pretty concise form, you can drag

00:07:18.619 --> 00:07:24.619
elements around, you can move them, you can resize them, and it builds your UI doing that.

00:07:25.619 --> 00:07:29.619
And don't worry, we're going to show a little bit more about that in a few minutes.

00:07:29.619 --> 00:07:31.619
The Shiny UI Editor is also an R package.

00:07:31.619 --> 00:07:35.619
It's not a very interesting R package, there's really one function that you're going to be

00:07:35.619 --> 00:07:37.619
using, which is launch editor.

00:07:37.619 --> 00:07:38.619
But that's how you get it.

00:07:38.619 --> 00:07:43.619
You go just like any other R package and install it that way that you get the Shiny UI Editor.

00:07:44.619 --> 00:07:50.619
So more philosophically, the Shiny UI Editor is an attempt to help you focus on kind of

00:07:50.619 --> 00:07:51.619
the fun stuff.

00:07:51.619 --> 00:07:57.619
And if you've ever spent a bunch of time doing things like tweaking a plot size or making

00:07:57.619 --> 00:08:02.619
a column slightly bigger by incrementing a pixel value up and testing it, you kind of

00:08:02.619 --> 00:08:03.619
know what I mean.

00:08:03.619 --> 00:08:07.619
And the UI Editor is really an attempt to take that away, let you just visually drag

00:08:07.619 --> 00:08:11.619
it where you want it to be, and then let the UI Editor write the code for you.

00:08:13.619 --> 00:08:17.619
So now that we've established kind of what the UI Editor is, let's talk about, I think

00:08:17.619 --> 00:08:19.619
just as importantly, what the UI Editor is not.

00:08:20.619 --> 00:08:23.619
The UI Editor is not a new UI framework.

00:08:23.619 --> 00:08:29.619
It provides like a visual way of declaring the UI for your app, but it writes that in

00:08:29.619 --> 00:08:31.619
whatever framework you want.

00:08:31.619 --> 00:08:36.619
However, we hope that you really like GridLayout right now, because that's the only supported

00:08:36.619 --> 00:08:37.619
layout.

00:08:37.619 --> 00:08:42.619
And this is actually kind of a little historical quirk that when we started this whole journey,

00:08:42.619 --> 00:08:47.619
we started with GridLayout, and then I made a little visual editor for editing those tables.

00:08:48.619 --> 00:08:52.619
And then it was quickly realized that there's more here, let's expand this.

00:08:52.619 --> 00:08:56.619
But right now, you use the UI Editor, you're also using GridLayout, but that's going to

00:08:56.619 --> 00:08:57.619
change in the future.

00:08:59.619 --> 00:09:03.619
So kind of on the same vein, it's not going to lock you into using it.

00:09:03.619 --> 00:09:09.619
So by virtue of it just writing code for you, if you don't want to use it, you just stop

00:09:09.619 --> 00:09:13.619
using it, and you just start editing your code like you would edit any other shiny app.

00:09:13.619 --> 00:09:17.619
Maybe your app is too complex for the visual editor.

00:09:17.619 --> 00:09:21.619
And maybe you just are using too many things that are not supported in it right now.

00:09:21.619 --> 00:09:22.619
That's fine.

00:09:22.619 --> 00:09:26.619
You're not going to have to go back to the beginning and rewrite your app from scratch.

00:09:26.619 --> 00:09:30.619
And we really put a fair amount of effort into making sure that the code the editor

00:09:30.619 --> 00:09:33.619
produces is human readable.

00:09:33.619 --> 00:09:36.619
So this is something that has been really important to us.

00:09:37.619 --> 00:09:42.619
And so kind of in a similar vein, Shiny UI Editor is not ready for production.

00:09:42.619 --> 00:09:44.619
But it writes code for you.

00:09:45.619 --> 00:09:49.619
And so in theory, if that code works and does what you want, go for it.

00:09:49.619 --> 00:09:51.619
But it's still very early.

00:09:51.619 --> 00:09:53.619
It's in this alpha stage.

00:09:53.619 --> 00:09:56.619
We just haven't had that many hands on it.

00:09:56.619 --> 00:10:02.619
And so we really are looking forward to having everybody get their hands on it, file issues,

00:10:02.619 --> 00:10:07.619
find areas that you find nice about it and what you wish it could do.

00:10:07.619 --> 00:10:12.619
But don't trust that you're going to go home after this and immediately start using it

00:10:12.619 --> 00:10:14.619
for your production app.

00:10:15.619 --> 00:10:19.619
So Shiny UI Editor is also not available for Python.

00:10:19.619 --> 00:10:25.619
So you may have noticed that RStudio slash NowPosit and the Shiny team have been making

00:10:25.619 --> 00:10:27.619
inroads in the Python community.

00:10:27.619 --> 00:10:29.619
But the UI editor has not.

00:10:29.619 --> 00:10:33.619
So this is just for Shiny for R right now.

00:10:33.619 --> 00:10:38.619
That being said, as both the UI editor and Shiny for Python mature,

00:10:38.619 --> 00:10:41.619
the goal is to bring it to Shiny for Python as well.

00:10:42.619 --> 00:10:45.619
Okay, so now that we've kind of established what it is and what it isn't,

00:10:45.619 --> 00:10:48.619
let's talk about the workflow of using the UI editor.

00:10:48.619 --> 00:10:52.619
So we start by launching the editor with that function that we mentioned before launch editor.

00:10:52.619 --> 00:10:54.619
You point it at your app location.

00:10:54.619 --> 00:10:58.619
And this application can exist or it might not exist.

00:10:58.619 --> 00:11:01.619
And if it doesn't exist, we'll ask you a few questions.

00:11:01.619 --> 00:11:06.619
And you can start with template app that UI editor friendly.

00:11:06.619 --> 00:11:09.619
Once you've done that, the UI editor spins up a browser window.

00:11:09.619 --> 00:11:12.619
You can use the visual interface to edit your app code.

00:11:12.619 --> 00:11:16.619
And then you close your browser window and you enjoy the app.

00:11:17.619 --> 00:11:19.619
Optionally, you can rinse and repeat.

00:11:19.619 --> 00:11:21.619
And I think that this is really important.

00:11:21.619 --> 00:11:24.619
We're not setting this UI editor up to be a way that you start your app

00:11:24.619 --> 00:11:27.619
and then you go on to never using it again.

00:11:27.619 --> 00:11:32.619
It can ingest app that it wrote, ingest app that theory didn't write.

00:11:32.619 --> 00:11:38.619
And then so you can have it kind of carry you through your whole Shiny app development process.

00:11:38.619 --> 00:11:40.619
Maybe later on, you need to add a new plot.

00:11:40.619 --> 00:11:45.619
You can do that with the UI editor, not just the way of setting up.

00:11:46.619 --> 00:11:51.619
Okay, so that's all good and interesting to hear a bunch of tech snippets

00:11:51.619 --> 00:11:53.619
and me read about what the UI editor is.

00:11:53.619 --> 00:11:54.619
This is the visual tool.

00:11:54.619 --> 00:11:58.619
I think it's probably valuable to actually see what it looks like.

00:12:00.619 --> 00:12:03.619
I was going to do a live demo, but I was told...

00:12:03.619 --> 00:12:04.619
Uh-oh.

00:12:11.619 --> 00:12:12.619
There we go.

00:12:15.619 --> 00:12:16.619
Never safe.

00:12:16.619 --> 00:12:18.619
So we're going to start here.

00:12:18.619 --> 00:12:19.619
Quick.

00:12:19.619 --> 00:12:22.619
So we have a fresh RStudio project open.

00:12:22.619 --> 00:12:23.619
There's nothing in it.

00:12:23.619 --> 00:12:25.619
You can see in the files pane.

00:12:25.619 --> 00:12:26.619
It's pretty small.

00:12:26.619 --> 00:12:27.619
I apologize for that.

00:12:27.619 --> 00:12:29.619
But there's nothing sitting in there.

00:12:29.619 --> 00:12:34.619
And so we've run this launch editor function and pointed it to the current app directory.

00:12:34.619 --> 00:12:36.619
And it says, we can't find an app.

00:12:36.619 --> 00:12:38.619
So we fill out some template.

00:12:39.619 --> 00:12:42.619
So it says, yeah, we want to create a new app from a template.

00:12:42.619 --> 00:12:44.619
And so we say, yes, we do.

00:12:44.619 --> 00:12:46.619
And then it asks us what template we want.

00:12:46.619 --> 00:12:48.619
So we have a couple templates right now.

00:12:48.619 --> 00:12:49.619
Rewind this.

00:12:52.619 --> 00:12:53.619
A couple templates.

00:12:53.619 --> 00:12:54.619
So there's geyser templates.

00:12:54.619 --> 00:12:56.619
And then there's this chickweight template.

00:12:56.619 --> 00:13:02.619
And I don't know about you guys, but my very first job was actually as a chicken farmer

00:13:02.619 --> 00:13:05.619
before I had this cushy software developer job.

00:13:05.619 --> 00:13:09.619
And so I was not a park ranger at Yellowstone, so I'm not going to use the geyser app.

00:13:09.619 --> 00:13:11.619
I'm going to do chickweights.

00:13:11.619 --> 00:13:13.619
We've seen enough geysers, I think.

00:13:13.619 --> 00:13:15.619
So we choose that chickweight.

00:13:15.619 --> 00:13:18.619
It spins up the UI editor, and this is what we have.

00:13:18.619 --> 00:13:20.619
And so this is in a browser tab.

00:13:20.619 --> 00:13:23.619
And so looking at what we have here, we start.

00:13:23.619 --> 00:13:25.619
We have this element panel on the left.

00:13:25.619 --> 00:13:28.619
You can drag and drop elements from that into your app.

00:13:28.619 --> 00:13:31.619
And then in the middle, there's this kind of app pane.

00:13:31.619 --> 00:13:32.619
It's a skeleton.

00:13:32.619 --> 00:13:33.619
It's not exactly your app even.

00:13:33.619 --> 00:13:35.619
We have a faux plot there.

00:13:35.619 --> 00:13:37.619
And on the right, we have a properties panel.

00:13:37.619 --> 00:13:41.619
This properties panel tells you things like where the element is within your UI tree.

00:13:41.619 --> 00:13:44.619
And then you also have an app preview.

00:13:44.619 --> 00:13:47.619
That app main window that you saw isn't perfect.

00:13:47.619 --> 00:13:51.619
So if you really need to see what your app looks like, you can use the preview.

00:13:51.619 --> 00:13:54.619
And so we have two plots on top of each other here.

00:13:54.619 --> 00:13:57.619
And maybe we want to put those plots next to each other.

00:13:57.619 --> 00:14:01.619
So we can do that just by reaching up and adding a new column.

00:14:01.619 --> 00:14:04.619
We can drag one of the plots over and drag one of the plots up.

00:14:04.619 --> 00:14:06.619
Now we have this whole empty row on the bottom.

00:14:06.619 --> 00:14:07.619
We can just delete that.

00:14:07.619 --> 00:14:09.619
And so we can check to make sure that that works.

00:14:09.619 --> 00:14:14.619
And our app is updated kind of instantly to build that new layout.

00:14:14.619 --> 00:14:17.619
And so from there, we might say, you know,

00:14:17.619 --> 00:14:23.619
maybe let's shrink this column on the left and emphasize the line plot on the right.

00:14:23.619 --> 00:14:26.619
Do that, and it automatically updates.

00:14:26.619 --> 00:14:29.619
And so one of the things we might want to do also is right now,

00:14:29.619 --> 00:14:34.619
the number of lines that are shown in that plot is given via a numeric input.

00:14:34.619 --> 00:14:36.619
But maybe we want to use a slider.

00:14:36.619 --> 00:14:37.619
So we can delete that element.

00:14:37.619 --> 00:14:42.619
We can drag a slider input in, go to the input ID, change it to numChick,

00:14:42.619 --> 00:14:45.619
which is what that reactive input is set as.

00:14:45.619 --> 00:14:48.619
And then we can go and change the value.

00:14:48.619 --> 00:14:51.619
So we're going to say min 1, 20.

00:14:51.619 --> 00:14:54.619
And we're going to use a step size of 1.

00:14:54.619 --> 00:14:57.619
And then we can change the label to say number of chick.

00:14:57.619 --> 00:15:00.619
And then we can go back to the app preview to see if that works.

00:15:00.619 --> 00:15:01.619
And we can drag it.

00:15:01.619 --> 00:15:05.619
See, yep, the app is actively updated, and it is working.

00:15:05.619 --> 00:15:08.619
So this kind of workflow of going back and forth between the preview

00:15:08.619 --> 00:15:11.619
and the editor is what we envision people doing.

00:15:11.619 --> 00:15:13.619
The next we might want to change the title.

00:15:13.619 --> 00:15:14.619
So it says ChickWaste right now.

00:15:14.619 --> 00:15:20.619
Let's change it to RStudioCon 2022, and we'll left-align it.

00:15:20.619 --> 00:15:24.619
So we can see in the little tiny preview on the bottom that it updated.

00:15:24.619 --> 00:15:26.619
But I want to emphasize another point,

00:15:26.619 --> 00:15:29.619
which is the fact that you can edit the code as well.

00:15:29.619 --> 00:15:33.619
So we go into the app code that the UI editor generated for us.

00:15:33.619 --> 00:15:35.619
Obviously, there was nothing there.

00:15:35.619 --> 00:15:39.619
And what we can see, we can find this RStudioCon 2022.

00:15:39.619 --> 00:15:42.619
And let's change that right in the code.

00:15:42.619 --> 00:15:45.619
So let's make it positive.

00:15:45.619 --> 00:15:50.619
And 2022, but make sure it's an integer, so we'll add an L.

00:15:50.619 --> 00:15:54.619
Then we save that, and we go back, and the UI editor is automatically updated.

00:15:54.619 --> 00:15:58.619
And so this is really emphasizing that we have this workflow of, you know,

00:15:58.619 --> 00:16:01.619
some things might be easier to do in the UI editor,

00:16:01.619 --> 00:16:03.619
and some things might be easier to do in code,

00:16:03.619 --> 00:16:05.619
and we don't want to hold you back.

00:16:05.619 --> 00:16:07.619
We want the UI editor to just sit there.

00:16:07.619 --> 00:16:10.619
Maybe you just want to use it to resize columns or, you know, add a new plot,

00:16:10.619 --> 00:16:14.619
but you want to type your contents or whatever by hand.

00:16:14.619 --> 00:16:17.619
You can go back and forth between the code and the UI editor,

00:16:17.619 --> 00:16:20.619
leave it up, and just edit your app as you go.

00:16:20.619 --> 00:16:24.619
And so we can just check now to make sure that that works.

00:16:24.619 --> 00:16:26.619
We can open up the app that it generated.

00:16:26.619 --> 00:16:27.619
That's the app that it generated.

00:16:27.619 --> 00:16:30.619
And so it worked, which is good.

00:16:30.619 --> 00:16:34.619
Given that I prerecorded this demo, that would be pretty bad if it didn't work.

00:16:34.619 --> 00:16:36.619
Okay.

00:16:39.619 --> 00:16:44.619
Okay, so quickly, I just want to talk about the philosophy of the UI editor.

00:16:44.619 --> 00:16:47.619
So one thing that you might be asking at this point is,

00:16:47.619 --> 00:16:52.619
how do we avoid some of the common pitfalls of no-code solutions?

00:16:52.619 --> 00:16:55.619
Because the UI editor is, in a way, a no-code solution.

00:16:55.619 --> 00:16:59.619
And this is something that we were very careful about when we started.

00:17:00.619 --> 00:17:05.619
And I think the simplest answer to that is that it's not a no-code editor.

00:17:05.619 --> 00:17:07.619
Fundamentally, we're writing code.

00:17:07.619 --> 00:17:10.619
The UI editor is a visual interface,

00:17:10.619 --> 00:17:13.619
but everything goes immediately back to code and vice versa.

00:17:13.619 --> 00:17:16.619
And so really, I don't think of it as no-code.

00:17:16.619 --> 00:17:20.619
I really think of it as a fancy auto-complete.

00:17:20.619 --> 00:17:22.619
You know, you might be able to tab-complete something,

00:17:22.619 --> 00:17:23.619
and it does what you want.

00:17:23.619 --> 00:17:26.619
This is essentially doing that for your UI.

00:17:27.619 --> 00:17:32.619
And so we also really tried to keep it as simple as we possibly could,

00:17:32.619 --> 00:17:36.619
because one of the things that happens with no-code editors

00:17:36.619 --> 00:17:41.619
is that code is an extremely wonderful medium for expressing yourself.

00:17:41.619 --> 00:17:45.619
RStudio is really a proponent of the power of code.

00:17:45.619 --> 00:17:48.619
And so the problem with that extreme flexibility

00:17:48.619 --> 00:17:53.619
is that there's a lot of solution space that you need to make available

00:17:53.619 --> 00:17:56.619
if you really want to fully explore that.

00:17:56.619 --> 00:17:59.619
And so visually mapping to that space can be really intense.

00:17:59.619 --> 00:18:01.619
So we really carefully pulled everything back

00:18:01.619 --> 00:18:04.619
to make sure that we just let you edit your UI code.

00:18:04.619 --> 00:18:07.619
You can move things. You can set some settings.

00:18:07.619 --> 00:18:10.619
We're really not trying to go crazy and let you do everything,

00:18:10.619 --> 00:18:13.619
because we found that in a lot of tools that do that,

00:18:13.619 --> 00:18:15.619
you actually might as well just learn how to code

00:18:15.619 --> 00:18:19.619
instead of some, you know, esoteric visual editor,

00:18:19.619 --> 00:18:22.619
because at least then you know how to code.

00:18:22.619 --> 00:18:26.619
You don't have some skill that's not going to work anywhere else.

00:18:26.619 --> 00:18:29.619
And so I think the last and most important part about it

00:18:29.619 --> 00:18:32.619
is that this is the shiny UI editor.

00:18:32.619 --> 00:18:34.619
And that's an important fact,

00:18:34.619 --> 00:18:38.619
is the UI editor is not the shiny app editor.

00:18:38.619 --> 00:18:40.619
We're not trying to write your server code.

00:18:40.619 --> 00:18:42.619
We want you to write that.

00:18:42.619 --> 00:18:44.619
We think that you're the best person to do that.

00:18:44.619 --> 00:18:46.619
We want you as a data scientist to write your cool plots

00:18:46.619 --> 00:18:48.619
and your good models and all that stuff.

00:18:48.619 --> 00:18:51.619
We're just going to make it a little bit easier for you

00:18:51.619 --> 00:18:53.619
to build the UI for you.

00:18:53.619 --> 00:18:56.619
We don't want you to have to be an expert web developer

00:18:56.619 --> 00:19:00.619
to create nice-looking layouts for your app.

00:19:00.619 --> 00:19:04.619
So the UI editor is the UI editor, not the server editor.

00:19:04.619 --> 00:19:06.619
It's not a full no-code solution.

00:19:06.619 --> 00:19:09.619
That being said, there are solutions out there

00:19:09.619 --> 00:19:12.619
that are full no-code that write the server code for you.

00:19:12.619 --> 00:19:15.619
And there's actually a talk coming up after this

00:19:15.619 --> 00:19:19.619
that I'm pretty excited to see does just that.

